(pre-emptively locked replies in case any souls fanboys turn up but yeah. you can absolutely make a difficult game but still have it accessible to disabled people, and you can still include "easy modes" without taking away the option for added difficulty at *player's choice*.) https://t.co/5hRw6b5zLV

easy mode also doesn't work for everyone bc it tends to universally adjust settings rather than specific adaptions that people might need. and even if a game *does* include an easy mode, that's still not going to change that YOU can play it however hard you want to!

having accessibility settings to make it playable for disabled gamers is not the same thing as "easy mode." I promise you're not going to take away the souls environment and gameplay style by adding toggles and options to make it better adapted to individual needs

the thing is you can still make souls games that are challenging while making it accessible to *everyone.* Having settings for colourblindness, Deaf players, mobility issues etc does NOT take away from the overall atmosphere. Disability should not be an afterthought.

So far 2022 has just been a lot of acceptance of things I kept suppressed without even realising it. Accepting loss, accepting struggles, accepting pain and just trying to come to terms with it. I think I've really come a long way, I'm proud of myself 😁

These past few years I've had a lot of sudden deaths and stuff like that in the family and I don't think I coped much. I was just denying my feelings until recently. I didn't realise I was denying this as well. But I think I'm in a much better place now than I was back then 💛

I don't usually talk about religion much on here bc I always worry its maybe uncomfortable or just not interesting 😅 but I do feel a lot happier in accepting it's important to me. I feel a little sad that I felt so lost for so many years, but better late than never? Haha

I've been working so hard in other areas to get healthy again both physically and emotionally but I really neglected the spiritual side until recently. I didn't realise how much it meant to me. But with purim and everything I just feel this kinda renewal in me. Feels great 💛

I just need to go back to the rabbi because I miss her so much 😔 I feel very guilty about missing shul but i was juist not in a healthy state for years. But I think she would understand. I just hope she will forgive that my hebrew pronunciation has maybe slipped a tiny bit 😅

I think I'm at a point in my life where I can finally say that I'm ready to commit myself back to my faith. I really struggled with it for so many years with grief and depression and just finding myself lost for a long time but I'm in a much better place now. I think it's time 💛

honestly so far 2022 has just been me realising I've slowly got stuck in unhealthy patterns and just finding ways to slowly and gently get myself out while not tearing myself down for it. I don't think I could have done this even 2 years ago but I do feel a lot better now 🌻

I used to be so hugely self critical all the time of ever struggling and thinking I shouldn't ever ask for help, but now I'm trying to take a more caring and gentle approach to myself. And honestly it's been really helping me to just recognise that needing support is okay too 💛

I think one of the best things that ever happened to me was instead of thinking of my depressive episodes as setbacks in recovery, now I class my MH as high/low support times, bc when I'm really in it, I need more support, but it doesn't mean I've somehow "failed" myself
